## 12. Global Failure Modes

- generic fade spam that replaces hierarchy with uniform softness
- all-at-once reveal that destroys beat logic and focal order
- slide-deck rhythm where every shot lasts the same amount of time
- overspeed luxury that tries to look premium by moving too fast
- glow-heavy fake premium motion that brightens instead of structuring
- motion louder than product, where page identity becomes secondary to spectacle
- copy animation replacing structure, causing headings to do the page’s job
- no hold state, so scenes never emotionally land
- over-symmetric pacing where every side behaves the same and no focal truth emerges
- no depth separation between page body, echo, chrome, runtime evidence, and hold-state layers

## 13. Production Notes

- This specification is still not code, but it is detailed enough to drive motion implementation without inventing timing scene by scene.
- Parameters that may be micro-tuned during implementation are exact milliseconds within the declared ranges, stagger offsets within token bands, and low-level spring damping values.
- Parameters that may not be casually changed are motion family choice for a given shot, focal precedence, delay order between primary and secondary layers, and the existence of final hold states.
- The scenes that should have timing locked first in implementation are S02 Home, S06 Intervals, S07 Scales, S11 Audio Core, S12 Position DNA, S14 Live Product, S19 Ecosystem, and S20 Closing.

