## 8. Batch B / C hard visibility

### Batch B trainer law
- Notes 练识字
- Intervals 练关系
- Scales 练系统
- Chords 练和声

Required visibility:
- Intervals must remain the flagship trainer base.
- Scales must put System in primary position.
- Notes must place Challenge at the L1 lower-right role.
- Notes must not elevate Flow to the primary layer.
- Chords must put Mode / Progression / Voice Leading on the main axis.
- Trainer family must not become four equal explanatory templates.

### Batch C system chain law
- Audio Candidate Export
- Position DNA / Position Likelihood
- Topology / Graph / Resolver / Harmonic Targets
- Semantic / Training Meaning
- Live Product

Required visibility:
- Audio Core is not a tuner appendix.
- Fretboard Core is not a technical poster.
- Position DNA / Position Likelihood must be a visible candidate-ranking layer.
- Live Product must be the real runtime landing of trainer -> core -> runtime.

---

## 9. Prohibited outcomes

The contract is violated if the result becomes:
- explanation board
- big segmented board
- premium-looking PPT
- full-screen explanatory text panel
- page-inside-page mockup deck
- product family overview wall
- dashboard card wall
- feature grid
- beautiful static keyframes with weak page bodies
- typography-led explanation replacing product structure
- minimum-delivery shortcut dressed up as polish

---

## 10. Acceptance doctrine

This contract is satisfied only if:
- the page body is always the main actor
- scenes are direct stage expressions of real upgraded product surfaces
- Batch B trainer boundaries are legible at the page-body level
- Batch C system chain is legible at the page-body level
- motion reveals structure, evidence, and handoff instead of decorating slides
- external mature implementation adoption is rich, material, and unmistakable
- the result cannot reasonably be mistaken for an explanation demo
- the result can guide future implementation as a visual development blueprint

If a reader can still mistake the output for a premium presentation deck, the contract has failed.
