# REAL_PAGE_BODY_FIRST_REVEAL_REBUILD_PLAN

## Purpose

This file is a rebuild plan for correcting the current standalone demo at the implementation level.
It does not continue the current polish direction.
It does not modify code by itself.
It defines what can be kept, what must be discarded, how reveal architecture must be rebuilt, and where the rebuild must restart from.

The diagnosis is:

- the current standalone demo has useful engineering shell assets
- but its page composition and reveal architecture still behave like a presentation system
- many surfaces still render too much at once
- `stepIndex` is often used as highlight switching instead of true shot-level orchestration
- the result still reads as deck-first rather than page-body-first

So the correct next move is not “more polish.”
The correct next move is a controlled rebuild of page composition and reveal architecture.

---

## A. What Can Be Kept

These assets may remain and be reused because they are engineering infrastructure, not the root of the product-type error.

### A1. Scene manager and progression runtime

Keep:

- top-level scene progression in `src/App.jsx`
- click / keyboard progression model
- scene index + step index state ownership
- `AnimatePresence` based scene switching baseline

Reason:
- the existence of a scene manager is not the problem
- the problem is what each scene renders and how step state is used inside page bodies

### A2. Stage and chrome foundation

Keep as reusable shell assets:

- `StageBackdrop.jsx`
- `PresentationChrome.jsx`
- `StageFrame.jsx`
- `LensStage.jsx`
- shared stage container logic
- progress display baseline

Reason:
- these are reusable cinematic infrastructure
- they should become subordinate to page bodies, not be thrown away automatically

### A3. Shared primitives and UI wrappers

Keep as reusable base layer:

- `SurfacePrimitives.jsx`
- local UI wrappers under `src/components/ui/*`
- locally adapted mature source modules
- motion-capable shell primitives

Reason:
- the primitives themselves are not the failure
- the failure is how they are being assembled into page compositions

### A4. External dependency adoption baseline

Keep:

- Motion integration approach
- Magic UI adaptation approach
- shadcn primitive adaptation approach
- local wrapper strategy for external mature implementations

Reason:
- dependency adoption is already on the right technical path
- what needs correction is where these implementations land and what they serve

### A5. File/folder decomposition baseline

Keep the broad decomposition pattern as a starting point:

- `src/components/presentation/chrome/*`
- `src/components/presentation/surfaces/*`
- `src/data/product-scenes.js`
- scene-to-surface registry in `ProductSurfaces.jsx`

Reason:
- folder organization is usable
- but the surface implementations inside these folders must be selectively rebuilt

### A6. Valuable current implementation assets

Keep only as reference material, not as final direction:

- parts of current dark stage shell logic
- some panel framing code
- some motion wrappers
- some candidate/evidence panel code in core family
- some navigation/theme shell ideas

Rule:
- these are technical reuse candidates
- they are not proof that current page compositions are correct

---

## B. What Must Be Discarded

These parts must not be polished forward.
They are not “unfinished good direction.”
They are wrong-direction assets.

### B1. All-at-once page composition

Must discard:

- surfaces that render almost the entire page body immediately
- layouts where all major panels are visible from the first beat
- step logic that only toggles active state while leaving all structural content visible

Why:
- this directly violates `no all-at-once reveal`
- it creates explanation-board behavior even when the visuals are premium

### B2. Explanation-oriented page bodies

Must discard:

- Why Different as a comparison board
- Navigation as a navigation-introduction page
- Theme as a settings-explanation page
- any surface where the primary content is “what this page means”
- any surface where text explains upgrade logic more than the page body demonstrates it

Why:
- page meaning must come from page structure and object reveal
- not from explanatory composition

### B3. Step logic that only changes highlight, label, or badge state

Must discard:

- surfaces where `stepIndex` only changes:
  - chip active state
  - sidebar selection
  - small metric values
  - tiny color differences
  - label emphasis

Why:
- this is not shot-level reveal orchestration
- it produces “slide 1 / slide 2 / slide 3” behavior instead of cinematic product staging

### B4. Deck-first layout logic

Must discard:

- wide presentation-first containers that dominate page identity
- page-inside-page reading
- “hero explanation + body demo block” composition
- surfaces that look like stage boards with embedded UI examples

Why:
- the page itself must be the stage
- not a staged explanation of a page

### B5. Trainer family templating

Must discard:

- any attempt to make Intervals / Scales / Notes / Chords feel like four equal card-based surfaces
- any composition where family consistency erases trainer identity

Why:
- trainer family continuity is required
- trainer family sameness is forbidden

### B6. Core family posterization

Must discard:

- Audio Core as a technical system board
- Fretboard Core as a graph poster
- Position DNA as a caption or subpanel
- Live Product as a summary sheet

Why:
- core family must be productized system surfaces
- not visually upgraded documentation

### B7. Style drift away from real current product DNA

Must discard:

- any page body that no longer feels connected to the current repo’s:
  - mobile-first density logic
  - trainer central-stage logic
  - bottom navigation DNA
  - tool/setup restraint
  - current product interaction language

Why:
- the upgraded product must feel like the same product family
- not a separate keynote-dark universe

---

## C. How Reveal Architecture Must Be Rebuilt

The rebuild must convert scene state from slide logic into shot logic.

### C1. Replace `stepIndex as highlight switch` with `stepIndex as shot orchestration state`

Current wrong model:

- page renders all major structural objects
- `stepIndex` changes emphasis only

Required new model:

- every `stepIndex` corresponds to a real shot or beat state
- each shot decides which objects are:
  - entering
  - becoming focal
  - shifting to echo
  - folding back
  - remaining hidden
  - dropping as runtime overlay
  - resolving into hold state

Implementation consequence:
- surfaces must stop thinking in “render whole page, then style it”
- surfaces must start thinking in “render staged object graph based on shot truth”

### C2. Introduce explicit shot orchestration inside page bodies

Each rebuilt surface must define an internal shot map such as:

- `shot 0`: page seed state
- `shot 1`: primary focal object enters
- `shot 2`: secondary supporting object appears
- `shot 3`: system-depth layer becomes visible
- `shot 4`: runtime evidence layer descends
- `shot 5`: previous focal object side-shifts
- `shot 6`: handoff target is prepared
- `shot 7`: hold state

This must be object-based, not page-container-based.

### C3. Rebuild around layer discipline

Each rebuilt page must explicitly separate:

- `page body layer`
- `focal layer`
- `secondary echo layer`
- `system-depth layer`
- `runtime evidence layer`
- `chrome layer`
- `overlay layer`
- `hold-state layer`

Required timing law:

- page body appears first
- focal object establishes the page’s identity
- secondary echo follows later
- system-depth cannot appear before page identity is readable
- runtime evidence cannot appear before there is something to prove
- chrome must support, not dominate
- hold-state adds no new explanation

### C4. Replace full-surface fade with object choreography

Current wrong pattern:

- one `motion.div` wraps the whole scene
- whole surface blurs/fades/slides in

Required new pattern:

- outer scene transition remains minimal
- meaningful motion moves to object level:
  - title cluster
  - active control group
  - page body panel
  - side echo card
  - evidence layer
  - runtime overlay
  - handoff strip

The whole page may still transition between scenes, but within-scene truth must come from object choreography.

### C5. Required shot behaviors by type

#### focal object behavior
- must establish page identity
- must appear before explanatory copy
- may migrate, shrink, or side-shift later

#### secondary echo behavior
- may retain prior information
- must never compete with the focal object
- must arrive after the focal object is readable

#### system-depth behavior
- must appear only after the page body is established
- must not become diagram theater

#### runtime evidence behavior
- must descend as proof
- must feel operational, not decorative
- must be attached to the product logic of the page

#### hold-state behavior
- no new explanatory content
- only retained product truth
- must support cinematic closure

### C6. Required motion grammar during rebuild

Use the existing motion doctrine, but now as implementation law:

- `push-in`
  - for primary focal establishment
- `side-shift`
  - when an existing focal object yields center
- `fold-back`
  - when a finished object remains as context
- `overlay-drop`
  - when runtime/system overlays become operational
- `chain-handoff`
  - when meaning moves from one product object to another
- `dim-retain`
  - when prior context must stay visible without competing
- `semantic-lock`
  - when the scene reaches interpretable truth and stops adding ambiguity
- `final-hold`
  - when the scene completes without expanding into new explanation

### C7. Required state model for rebuilt surfaces

Every rebuilt page should be able to answer at runtime:

- what is the current focal object?
- what is still hidden?
- what is echo-only?
- what runtime evidence is active?
- what system-depth has been unlocked?
- what object will hand off to the next shot or scene?

If the surface cannot answer those questions, it is still operating in presentation mode.

### C8. Required data model additions

The rebuild may require introducing local scene/shot data such as:

- per-surface shot objects
- focal target ids
- reveal-order arrays
- visibility matrices
- overlay activation states
- evidence payload mock data
- handoff target descriptors

This is not optional if page-body-first reveal is to become real.

### C9. Anti-regression rule

During rebuild, every page must be checked against this question:

> If all explanatory copy were removed, would the viewer still understand what real upgraded product surface is being shown?

If the answer is no, the rebuild is not done.

---

## D. Real Product Starting Points

The rebuild must not restart from generic stage composition.
It must restart from real current product pages and product DNA.

### D1. Home must be rebuilt directly from `HomeView.jsx`

Home rebuild starting point:

- current greeting + hero + content-feed structure
- current recommendation and weakness routing DNA
- current layered card and entry logic

Correct rebuild direction:

- not “a page explaining the new Home”
- not “a stage with a mini Home inside”
- but a real upgraded Home page body that:
  - places one central product route in focus
  - delays recommendation / ecosystem / continuity layers
  - retains route and weakness DNA
  - reads as the upgraded product’s main page, not as a homepage concept board

Home must prove:

- it still belongs to current SVU
- it no longer reads as content-led
- it is already a real upgraded product home

### D2. Intervals must be rebuilt directly from `IntervalsTrainer.jsx`

Intervals rebuild starting point:

- current flagship trainer identity
- current L0/L1/L2/L3 logic
- current prompt / stage / control layering
- current relationship-training DNA

Correct rebuild direction:

- not “a page about why Intervals is flagship”
- not “a premium layout summarizing Intervals architecture”
- but the upgraded Intervals trainer page itself, where:
  - L0 is truly primary
  - L1/L2/L3 are revealed in depth
  - relationship training remains the visible core truth
  - runtime overlays prove operation without turning the scene into a board

Intervals must prove:

- it is still the flagship trainer
- it is visibly descended from the current trainer
- it does not become a generic premium training page

### D3. Why Home and Intervals must be rebuilt first

These two pages are the best first rebuild anchors because:

- Home defines whether the whole product still feels like the same product
- Intervals defines whether trainer family rebuild can remain page-body-first
- if these two still collapse into explanation shells, the rest of the project will drift again

So they must be treated as proof pages:

- if Home is right, foundation/entry can proceed
- if Intervals is right, trainer family can proceed
- only then should the same rebuild logic be propagated across the rest of the system

### D4. How Fretboard / Audio must be handled

They must not be treated as exceptions just because they are system-first today.

They must be rebuilt as:

- productized system surfaces
- not explanation boards
- not architecture posters
- not dark technical plates detached from current product language

They should borrow from the current product:

- trainer stage logic
- control language
- floating chrome restraint
- runtime feedback cadence
- panel density discipline

Correct identity:

- `Audio Core` = operating system surface for session/detection/stabilizer/export/semantic output
- `Position DNA` = candidate ranking and evidence surface
- `Fretboard Core` = deep training-space system surface
- `Live Product` = the natural convergence page that reconnects system truth back into trainer truth

### D5. Rebuild sequence after this plan

After this plan, the correct practical rebuild order is:

1. rebuild Home page body composition and shot-level reveal
2. rebuild Intervals page body composition and shot-level reveal
3. verify that both no longer read as presentation surfaces
4. only then extend the rebuilt logic into:
   - Navigation
   - Theme
   - Scales
   - Notes
   - Chords
   - Core family
   - Utility / Identity / Ecosystem

### D6. Why this time will not slide back into presentation system

This rebuild plan prevents regression by changing the order of truth:

Old wrong order:
- build stage shell
- place page composition inside it
- add explanation text to clarify meaning

New required order:
- rebuild real upgraded page body
- define focal object and shot sequence inside that page
- let staging shell support it
- let copy only reinforce what the structure already proves

That is the only path that can produce:

- real upgraded product surfaces
- cinematic but product-first staging
- continuity with the current repo
- a result that can later flow back into implementation

---

## Acceptance Gate For The Rebuild

The rebuild is only acceptable if all of the following are true:

- the first rebuilt pages no longer look like explanation boards
- the first rebuilt pages no longer rely on page-inside-page composition
- `stepIndex` has become true shot orchestration, not highlight switching
- Home visibly grows from `HomeView.jsx`
- Intervals visibly grows from `IntervalsTrainer.jsx`
- explanatory copy could be reduced sharply without losing page meaning
- the result still feels like the same product, only upgraded

If any of those fail, the project has only changed cosmetics and has not actually corrected direction.
